Object Pool Design Pattern
--------------------------
"Instead of creating and destroying objects repeatedly, keep a pool of reusable objects — borrow, use, return."

Why Do We Need It?
Object creation is expensive (DB conn, threads). So, Create once, reuse many times

When To Use?
DB connections
Thread management
Socket/HTTP connections
Heavy parser/serializer instances
Game objects (bullets, particles)

Built-in Object Pools in Java & Spring
======================================

// Thread pool — most common Object Pool usage
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);
pool.submit(() -> System.out.println("Task"));

// ForkJoinPool — parallel task pool
ForkJoinPool fjPool = new ForkJoinPool(4);

// Integer cache — JVM pools -128 to 127
Integer a = 127;
Integer b = 127;
System.out.println(a == b); // true — same pooled object

Integer x = 128;
Integer y = 128;
System.out.println(x == y); // false — outside pool range, new objects

// String pool
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true — same pooled string literal
